				JSRHS Art Students Selected for NH Art Educator’s Annual Youth Art  Month Exhibit 




													Details							









					Last Updated: 12 March 2020				







  Print  

  Email 





Eight John Stark Regional High School art students have been invited to participate in the New Hampshire Art Educator’s Annual Youth Art Month (YAM) Exhibit at the NH State Library in Concord through March 22. The library is open Monday through Friday from 8-4:30 PM. The public is also invited to the exhibition reception on Sunday, March 22 from 1-3 PM. The NH State Library is located at 20 Park Street, across from the State House. 

JSRHS students in this exhibition include Lauren Zervos, who has been selected to receive the YAM 2020 Commissioners’ Award for her Looking into the Distance (Charcoal), Eli Bryant, Love in Ruins (Charcoal), Summer Clement, Saddie (Oil Pastel), Stephanie Rodonis, Visible (Digital Photography), Maddie Dionne, Great Bay (Printmaking with Watercolor), Lydia Piscina, Jungle (Acrylic &amp; Resin), Sheridan O’Brien, Roaring 20s (Scanography Photograph), and Gracie Bolduc, Sassy Pants (Watercolor).

“The students in this exhibit have demonstrated rigor in the classroom, commitment to mastering the skills taught in class, and have worked to push creative boundaries,” said JSRHS teacher Tracy Travers. “They’ve developed an artistic voice and are using their art as a way to educate and communicate,” she continued. 

 John Stark senior Lauren Zervos will be presented with the 2020 Commissioners’ Award at the exhibit reception on March 22.

 Image 1: Looking into the Distance, charcoal by Lauren Zervos. Lauren earned the 2020 YAM Commissioners' Award for this piece.

Image 2: Saddie, oil pastel by junior Summer Clement

Image 3: Visible (digital photography) by junior Stephanie Rodonis as displayed at the NH Art Educator's Youth Art Month Exhibit.

 

Image 4: Roaring 20s (scanography photograph) by junior Sheridan O' Brien. 


























				JSRHS student qualifies to take invitational math exam




													Details							









					Last Updated: 06 March 2020				







  Print  

  Email 






John Stark Regional High School Junior Nathan Chasse has qualified for the American Invitational Mathematics Exam (AIME) based on his performance in the American Mathematics Competition. To qualify for the AIME, Nathan needed to score in the top 5% in the American Mathematics Competition. Nathan will take the American Invitational Mathematics Examination in mid-March. The exam is a 15-question, 3-hour test and the use of calculators is not allowed. Concepts typically covered on the AIME include topics in elementary algebra, geometry, trigonometry, as well as number theory, probability, and combinatorics. The AIME is also used to determine qualification for the United States Mathematical Olympiad.



 


























